title: Manhattan: Central Park - 5th Avenue - 69th Street

text:
(1)
1-7 East 69th Street, at, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Fifth Ave. The 5-story mansion directly at the corner is No. 1, while the 3-story former garage has no number. The vacant lots formerly were Nos. 3-7 and are at the rear of the former Marshall Field residence (Nos. 4-8 East 70th Street inclusive), where they formed a garden. This has lately been s old (See The New York Times- March 23, 1937) and the purchaser's will erect two
12-story apartment houses here.
March 29, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same. The 5-story mansion, No. 1 East 69th Street, was the Harriman
home.

5th Avenue, east side, at E. 69th Street, showing
private dellings at both the N.E. and S.E. corners. These in order are (or were) the Adolph Lewisohn (No.881), the E.H. Harriman (No. 1 E. 69th Street), the Ogden Mills (No.877)
and the Daniel J. Leary (No. 876) homes.
The N.Y. Herald Tribune of Sunday, June 18, 1939 carries a photo and an article reporting the details of the proposed replacement with an apartment house of the Harriman and possibly the Lewisohn homes. Sir John Mactaggart, a Scottish builder purchased the former 5 years ago and is about to procede with plans for this
site.
View 2 shows only the Lewisohn and Harriman homes while
No.3 features only the latter.
